{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c4f8b058-6a3f-4f05-8252-089f64c55613","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process and collect:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps                          # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the trace out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to Speedscope:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n# Open the .json at https://www.speedscope.app\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use the **sidecar approach** or enable [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) as a sidecar — it exposes a REST API for on-demand trace collection.\n- For **production-safe** continuous profiling, consider `dotnet-monitor` with the `/trace` endpoint, which avoids exec entirely.\n- `--duration 00:00:30` is usually enough to identify hot paths; adjust as needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"875fda32-eb22-4bb9-9440-5a123d4e99dc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":442,"requestId":"609D:B2C21:10C972F:14FCEE0:69FFDF77"},"id":"a208ea85-da91-41b7-b136-95e42e947e63","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:29:38.144Z","parentId":"89763a98-bb82-452d-bd56-a5998aacd37c"}
